WHAT WORKED, AND IT IS THE REUSABLE PART. The highest-yield pattern on this map was one sentence
shape: a US originator's 10-K discloses customer concentration and NAMES the big-three wholesalers,
because each is a >10% customer and the disclosure is mandatory. I verified it on Pfizer BEFORE
writing the worker prompts -- "McKesson, Inc. 25% / Cencora, Inc. 16% / Cardinal Health, Inc. 13%"
-- and shipped that worked example inside the prompt. It produced 17 of the map's 47 edges. This is
the counterparty-side recipe again: the distributor chokepoint was evidenced from the manufacturers'
filings, not the distributors'. Half the originators still anonymised it ("three wholesalers"), and
that split is gap-05-wholesaler-identity-anonymised rather than a silent absence.

TWO PRE-BURST FIXES THAT WOULD HAVE BEEN ABORTS AFTERWARDS. merge_edges.py had no pharma vocabulary
at all, and it ABORTS on an unknown relationship_type, so every staged edge would have been rejected
after the money was spent. And verify_edges.py's KEY held only the seven 05 names that
verify_sources.py needed for FINANCIAL citations -- but an EDGE is stricter, because its document
must name BOTH endpoints, so every company that can appear as a COUNTERPARTY needs its document-side
name too. Both landed before the fan-out, per the rule 04 wrote into merge_edges.py's own comments.

A GREEN SELFTEST DID NOT COVER THE NEW WORK. Both tools' suites passed after the edits -- and would
have passed identically without them, because no case touched the new entries. Driving the new
aliases directly, the first run reported ALL TWELVE positives failing and ALL negatives passing.
That shape is the dead-checker signature, not a data verdict: a matcher matching NOTHING fails every
control and passes every negative. The cause was in my harness, not the tool -- named() takes
(text, company) and I passed (company, text). Corrected: 20/20, both directions. The negatives are
the sharp half here: "Merck & Co" must NOT match Merck KGaA, and Scientific Protein Laboratories
must NOT be aliased to "SPL", because in FDA documents SPL means Structured Product Labeling.

THE EVERNORTH BINDING, which is the strongest edge on the map and the one a worker correctly
refused to write. Cencora's FY2025 10-K names its second-largest customer as "Evernorth Health
Services" at ~13% of revenue and never writes Cigna or Express Scripts -- measured, zero hits for
both. The worker logged it as an unevidenced flag rather than guess. It is closeable, but only with
a SECOND document: Cigna's own 10-K says in prose "We have two segments: Evernorth Health Services
and Cigna Healthcare" and tags it ci:EvernorthMember in its own XBRL. So Evernorth is a name Cigna
itself trades under, the alias meets this table's stated bar, and the edge now rests on two
documents -- Cencora's for the dependency and its size, Cigna's for the identity. Without it, a
big-three distributor depending on a big-three PBM's parent renders as no connection at all.

THE PRE-REGISTERED TESTS, RUN. FOUNDATION.md named the documents that would settle each hypothesis,
and two of the three "unreachable" verdicts from the burst were wrong:
  - FTC PBM report: a worker got 404 on two stale URLs and filed it unreachable. It is reachable at
    ftc.gov/system/files/ftc_gov/pdf/pharmacy-benefit-managers-staff-report.pdf and it settles
    hypothesis 4 outright: "the three largest PBMs now manage nearly 80 percent of all prescriptions
    filled in the United States", naming CVS Caremark, Express Scripts and OptumRx. Gap row deleted
    rather than left standing as a false claim of unreachability. CAVEAT CARRIED: the same report
    says the top SIX process >90%, so there is a tail below the big three.
  - BIOSECURE Act: congress.gov 403s an automated fetcher; the browser reaches it. The bill commonly
    called BIOSECURE is H.R.8333, NOT S.3558 -- S.3558 contains the word BIOSECURE zero times and
    names WuXi AppTec only. H.R.8333 defines a "biotechnology company of concern" as "BGI, MGI,
    Complete Genomics, WuXi AppTec, and WuXi Biologics", so FOUNDATION.md's naming claim is CORRECT.
    Its STATUS is not: last action 2024-09-10, referred to Senate committee, and the 118th Congress
    ended in January 2025, so that bill died. Whether it was reintroduced in the 119th is unknown --
    congress.gov's search returns a Cloudflare bot-detection interstitial, deliberately not bypassed.
  - FDA import alert 66-40 needed no browser at all; it is plain HTML. It carries a live red-list
    entry for "Changzhou SPL Company, Ltd." covering crude heparin since 2008 -- the episode this
    map cites. But it never writes "Scientific Protein Laboratories" (zero hits, as for Huahai and
    Hepalink), so the best available evidence for the crude-heparin chokepoint cannot be attached to
    the node. That is a contradiction row, not an edge.

## HONEST WEAKNESSES

- TWO OF SIX CHOKEPOINTS CARRY NO EDGE AT ALL: Zhejiang Huahai and Scientific Protein Laboratories,
  both in the API layer, which is hypothesis 1. No originator's filing names an active-ingredient
  supplier anywhere, and neither Chinese filing names a customer. This map is Mapped on the strength
  of its distributor, PBM and CDMO layers; its API layer is still hypothesis. 02 was labelled Mapped
  with three of five chokepoints unevidenced and that was called arguably wrong; this is 2 of 6, and
  both are named in open gap rows, which is the only reason review.py returns 0 must-resolve.
- 17 OF 47 EDGES (36%) ARE competes-with, and review.py's R4 fires on it. That is better than 02's
  47% and far worse than 04's zero. The 17 are not padding -- 6 are the three distributors naming
  ONLY each other, which is the direct test of "no fourth-scale alternative", and 11 are specific
  named ANDA and patent proceedings. But the honest reading is that this map's edge COUNT overstates
  its dependency map, and R4 should keep saying so.
- I DROPPED 8 SOURCED EDGES ON EDITORIAL GROUNDS, which is a judgement someone may disagree with.
  All 8 came from a single Dr. Reddy's 20-F sentence enumerating competitors, and would have made
  Dr. Reddy's the most-connected node on the map purely as an artifact of one filing's boilerplate,
  including "competes with" edges to three CDMOs. All 8 are kept in full, with their sources, in
  data/dropped_edges.csv, and restoring them is one merge_edges.py run. ⚠ That sentence first read
  "they are archived, not destroyed", which was TRUE WHEN WRITTEN AND ABOUT TO BECOME FALSE: the only
  copy was in a session scratchpad under /private/tmp, and this map's own _incoming/ is gitignored, so
  the archive would have evaporated while a public log went on claiming it existed. A claim that names
  a path a reader can open is checkable; "archived" is not. The substance worth keeping is that
  Dr. Reddy's names Huahai as one of SEVERAL API competitors, which cuts AGAINST our own chokepoint
  flag on Huahai.
- THE THREE negotiates-rebates-with EDGES ARE THE WEAKEST ON THE MAP and the worker said so first.
  They rest on a passage in Sanofi's own risk factors describing PBM formulary-exclusion leverage
  over manufacturers generally, not a Sanofi-specific rebate. They are marked medium confidence and
  should be the first rows re-examined.
- CATALENT'S TWO EDGES CAN NEVER BE REFRESHED. Both come from its FY2024 10-K, the last one it will
  ever file: Novo Holdings took it private in December 2024. Recorded as stale-evidence.
- FIVE COMPANIES REMAIN ISOLATED (Novartis, Huahai, Scientific Protein, Samsung Biologics, WuXi
  AppTec) and there is still no timeseries and no politics lens, so this is a thinner map than 01.
- NOT CHECKED: I read the sentence behind only two of the 47 edges by hand. verify_edges proves a
  document names both endpoints; it cannot prove the sentence means what the row says. The other 45
  descriptions are the workers' readings, unaudited by a second pair of eyes.
